    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1891-10-01T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1891-10-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="191" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d191">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Wharton</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">Egan</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1891-10-01">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 1,
                            1891</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. Egan is informed that the President desires to establish and maintain the
                        most friendly relations with Chile, but the right of asylum having been
                        tacitly, if not expressly, allowed to other foreign legations, and having
                        been exercised by our minister with the old Government in the interest and
                        for the safety of the adherents of the party now in power, the President can
                        not but regard the application of another rule, accompanied by acts of
                        disrespect to our legation, as the manifestation of <pb facs="0284" n="178" xml:id="pg_178"/> a most unfriendly spirit. Mr. Egan is instructed to
                        furnish a copy of this to the minister for foreign affairs and to take the
                        utmost precaution to prevent any abuse of the privilege of asylum by those
                        to whom he has extended it; their intercourse with outside persons, whether
                        by person or by letter, should be under his supervision and limited to the
                        most necessary and innocent matters. The discussion and adjustment of the
                        matter would probably be much facilitated were there an authorized agent of
                        Chile at Washington.</p>
            </div>
